  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are things you realized only in your senior year of college?",
  "response": "While I don't have personal experiences or realizations, I can share some common insights that many students often have during their senior year of college:\n\n1. **Importance of Networking**: Many students realize that building relationships with professors, peers, and industry professionals is crucial for future job opportunities.\n\n2. **Real-World Applications of Knowledge**: Students often understand how academic theories apply in real-world scenarios and how critical problem-solving skills are.\n\n3. **Time Management**: With the demands of coursework, job applications, and potential internships, students often realize the importance of effective time management.\n\n4. **Career Readiness**: Many seniors start to see the value of internships, part-time jobs, or volunteer experiences that enhance their resumes and make them more competitive in the job market.\n\n5. **Mental Health Awareness**: The pressures of final year can lead to a greater awareness of mental health, self-care, and the importance of maintaining a balance between work and life.\n\n6. **The Value of a Liberal Arts Education**: Students often come to appreciate the broad skills and perspectives gained from a diverse curriculum, even in specialized fields.\n\n7. **Diversity and Inclusion**: Many realize the significance of understanding diverse viewpoints and working collaboratively with people from different backgrounds in a globalized world.\n\n8. **Financial Literacy**: Students may start to understand the importance of managing student loans, budgeting, and personal finance as they prepare to enter the workforce.\n\n9. **Critical Thinking and Adaptability**: Many seniors develop a stronger ability to think critically and adapt to new situations, which are essential skills in any career.\n\n10. **Feeling Unprepared is Normal**: As graduation approaches, many students realize that feeling unprepared is common and that it\u2019s okay to seek guidance and support from mentors and peers.\n\nThese realizations often help shape their transition from college to the workforce and contribute to their personal growth.",
